        "class": "ital",
        "text": "outrun Peter, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and to have come first to the sepulchre. But concerning that part of the history relating to the resurrection, we shall reserve ourselves till we come to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "John 20:1-31",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 20:1-31",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". We now pass on to a piece of history relating to the evidencing of Christ’s resurrection, which is neither touched by Matthew nor by Luke. Mark toucheth it shortly, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Mark 16:12,13",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Mark 16:12",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ",13",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "After that he appeared in another form to two of them, as they walked, and went into the country. And they went and told it unto the residue; neither believed they them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " We shall now hear Luke giving us a more full and perfect account. ",
        "children": []
